fields.name: Symptom Relief
fields.description:
When stopping opioids you can get cravings for the drug and withdrawal symptoms:  body aches, anxiety, fatigue, sweating, fatigue, nausea, vomiting and diarrhea.

Methadone and buprenorphine stop withdrawal symptoms and reduce cravings. Naltrexone does not stop withdrawal but helps a little bit with craving in the long term.

fields.name: Where do I take the medication?
How does medicine get in my body?
Where do I take the medicine for the first 3 months?
fields.description:
In the beginning, methadone must be supervised - you must come into the clinic everyday to receive your dose. If you are stable after 3 months you can begin to take it at home 

Buprenorphine can be taken at home after you are stable in a few days. 

Naltrexone injection must be given in a clinic, but its given every month

fields.name: How do I start treatment?
fields.description:
Methadone can be started immediately. 

Buprenorphine requires several hours of being away from opioids before starting

Naltrexone requires complete detoxification from opioids before starting. You will be offered other medications for relief during this time.

fields.name: Common side effects
fields.description:
sleeping problems (too sleepy or insomnia) is most common in methadone, bupenorphine and opioids like heroin 

weight gain is most common in methadone

constipation is most common in methadone and opioids like heroin

sexual side effects are most common in methadone and opioids like heroin 

 headaches are most common in buprenorphine 

 injection pain is most common with naltrexone and opioids like heroin if injected

fields.name: Cost without insurance
fields.description:
Methadone: $300 per month (much lower with insurance) 

Buprenorphine sublingual: $200 per month (lower with insurance) 

Naltrexone: $1350 per month (may be lower with insurance) 

No medication: $1800 per month, estimated

fields.name: Risk of relapse
fields.description:
The longer you stay on medications like methadone and buprenorphine, the longer you are able to stay off opioids like heroin.

Naltrexone also helps you staff off opioids as long as you continue to use it. Some people have trouble staying on this medication.

fields.name: Intensity of withdrawal if you stop
fields.description:
Methadone: intense as opioids like heroin, lasts 6 weeks

Buprenorphine: milder than opioids like heroin, lasts 1 week

Naltrexone: no withdrawal 

Stopping without medication: no withdrawal but high risk of relapse

Using opioids like heroin: intense, lasts 1 week

fields.name: Risk of death right after stopping
fields.description:
Stopping methadone: High, then goes down, higher than using. 

Stopping buprenorphine: High, then goes down, higher than using.

Stopping Naltrexone: High, then goes down, higher than using.

No medicine: Can be higher than continuing to use

Continuing to Use: HIgher than being on medicine

fields.name: Life saving
fields.description:
Opioid use disorder increases the risk of death, from overdose, infection and other problems.

In a room of 30 people with opioid use disorder, 3 people can die.  

Medications help save lives by reducing this risk by half

fields.name: Stop Relapse
fields.description:
The longer you stay on medications like methadone and buprenorphine, the longer you are able to stay off opioids like heroin.

Naltrexone also helps you staff off opioids as long as you continue to use it. Some people have trouble staying on this medication. 

Stopping opioid use without medication has a high risk of relapse.

fields.name: Life Function
fields.description:
Research shows medication can improve your abilities for day-to-day life

(1) ↓ Legal problems - you will less likely be arrested 

(2) ↑ Relationships - you will improve your relationships with friends or family 

(3) ↑ Employment - you will more likely be able to work 

Stopping opioid use without medication you will get better at first, but there is a high risk of relapse and then getting worse.

fields.name: How the medicine gets in the body
fields.description:
Methadone is a liquid taken by mouth 

Buprenorphine is a pill or dissolvable tab taken by mouth

Naltrexone is an injection in the buttocks

Opioids like heroin can be taken as pills by mouth, snorting, or by injection

fields.title: What happens if you stop medication on your own
Have you ever taken any of the following drugs?
fields.description: Have you ever taken any of the following drugs

fields.title: Do I have opioid use disorder?
fields.description: Based on your previous use of opioids, answer the following questions:

fields.text: Did you ever need to use more opioids to get the same high as when you first started using opioids?
Did the idea of missing a fix (or dose) ever make you anxious or worried?
In the morning, did you ever use opioids to keep from feeling "dope sick" or did you ever feel "dope sick"?
Did you worry about your use of opioids?
Did you find it difficult to stop or not use opioids?
Did you ever need to spend a lot of time/energy on finding opioids or recovering from feeling high?
Did you ever miss important things like doctor's appointments, family/friend activities, or other things because of opioids?

fields.title: What are opioids?
fields.content: Opioids are a type of drug that includes heroin and prescription pain medications.

fields.title: What is an opioid use disorder?
fields.content: At first, a person might take these opioid drugs for medical reasons, or because of how these drugs make them feel.

fields.title: How do you treat opioid use disorder?
fields.content: We know from research that using medications has the most success for opioid use disorder.

fields.title: What are my choices for medications?
fields.content: There are 3 medications proven to help opioid use disorder.

fields.title: Daily Life on Medication
fields.content: In addition to feeling better, the day to day experience of medictation includes getting started, picking up the medication, taking the medicine into the body, common side effets, and cost.

fields.title: How Long is Treatment?
fields.content: Most patients need to stay in treatment for at least 3-5 years to get the full benefits of medications. If you have had opioid use disorder for a longer time, you may need an even longer time to heal.

fields.title: What is an opioid use disorder?
fields.content:
Over time, some people need to continue taking these drugs just to feel normal, even if it causes problems or even if it takes over their life.

They can find it difficult to quit on their own.

fields.title: How does treatment help in the short-term?
fields.content: Medications for opioid use disorder can calm the body’s system as the body gets used to being away from the drug. Two medication options treat withdrawal symptoms and decrease cravings.

fields.title: How does treatment help in the long-term?
fields.content:
Over time, medications help you:

  • Stay OFF illegal opioids
  • Reduce the risk of death from drugs and legal problems
  • Improve your health and mood
  • Help you connect to what matter to you, like family or work

fields.title: Methadone
fields.content:
Methadone is a liquid taken by mouth, once a day.

In the first 3 months, go to a clinic every day to take your medication. As you get stable, you may be able to take medication at home.

This medicine treats withdrawal and cravings.

fields.title: Buprenorphine
fields.content:
Buprenorphine forms include Suboxone (dissolving tab) or Subutex (pill). It is usually taken by mouth, once a day.
 

In the beginning you will need to stop using opioids like heroin for several hours, then you can start this medicine. After you get to a stable dose, you can take this medication at home. 

This medicine treats withdrawals and cravings.

fields.title: Naltrexone
fields.content:
Naltrexone is an injection that is also called Vivitrol. It is taken as an injection, in the buttocks, once a month.

The pill version does not work as well for opioid disorder, only for alcohol.

You must stop using any opioids for at least 7 days before starting this medication. You can get the injection in the clinic every month.

This medicine does not treat withdrawals; it helps a little bit with cravings. Instead you will get different medicines during the first 7 days to help with detox. This medicine blocks opioids like heroin.

fields.title: What is true of all medications?
fields.content:
All of these medications must be taken at the right dose and for a long time:

Most patients need 3-5 years to let the brain heal, some longer.

Methadone and buprenorphine help withdrawals,

but naltrexone does not (you will get other medications to help during detox)  

All the medicines decrease the risk of death, reduce opioid use, reduce cravings, and help people function better -- meaning thinking and feeling better, better health, relationships, ability to work, and less legal problems.

fields.title: Benefits of Medications
fields.content:
You can compare different medications and no medication. The bigger the solid circle, the bigger the benefit for that option and category. 

Click on the row to learn more.

fields.title: How Do I End Treatment?
fields.content: If you and your doctor decide it is time to end treatment, this can be done slowly so you will not have much withdrawal symptoms.

fields.title: What happens if I stop treatment on my own?
fields.content:
If treatment is stopped quickly, on your own or because of things outside your control, you can have withdrawal symptoms. 

An important thing to remember is after you stop using opioids or medications for a while, your tolerance to opioids go down - that means your body is not used to the opioids anymore. That means if there is relapse and you use again, there is a higher risk of overdose.
